[[File:JohannPeterBerg.jpg|thumb|Johann Peter Berg]] '''Johann Peter Berg''' (September 3, 1737 – March 3, 1800) was a [[Germany|German]] [[Protestantism|Protestant]] [[theologian]], historian, and [[oriental studies|Orientalist]].
Berg was born in [[Bremen]], and studied at [[Leiden University]]. In 1762 he became Professor of [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[Languages of Asia|Oriental]] languages at the [[University of Bremen]], but moved in 1763 to the [[University of Duisburg]], where he taught nearly until his death in Duisburg in 1800. He translated various [[Arabic language|Arabic]] works, and lectured on a wide range of theological subjects. He also published an annotated copy of the Arabic dictionary of [[Jacobus Golius|Golius]], which served as the basis for that of [[Georg Freytag|Freytag]].
==Works== * ''Specimen Philol. ad Selecta V. T. Loca'' (Leiden, 1761) * ''Reformationsgeschichte der Länder Jülich, Cleve, Berg, Mark'' (Hamm, 1826, ed. by Tross)
